# Solo Maintainer Governance

Nicky is the sole developer for the foreseeable future. The agent acts as a
**maintainer partner**: flag drift early, keep docs truthful, and surface deferred
work during **planning** — not as a nagging layer (see README posture on out-of-scope
chase features).

## 0. Design before build (required)

When the user starts **designing** a new feature (before implementation):

1. Read `docs/tabled.md` for the matching department/platform.
2. List concerns **one by one** — issues, clarifications, questions, improvements.
   Do this proactively; do not wait to be asked.
3. Expect **2–3 back-and-forth rounds** until scope is agreed; only then write code.
4. Use `docs/plans/<topic>.md` for the design + build-session instructions.
5. **After ship:** fold outcomes into handbooks + `memory.md`, update `project_install.md`
   if needed, remove shipped rows from `docs/tabled.md`, **delete the plan file**.

**One concern per session** when building: one ship unit (agent slice, platform, or doc pass)
per thread when possible.

## 1. Rule compliance (flag, don't silently fix scope)

Before shipping or when reviewing design, cross-check work against `.cursor/rules/`:

| Area | Rule file |
|------|-----------|
| Agents (tree, SDK, runtime) | `agent-organization`, `agent-construction`, `agent-runtime`, `agent-scheduling`, `agent-eval`, `agent-onboarding`, `agent-lifecycle` |
| Wiki / Notion | `wiki-data-flow`, `naming`, `access-control` |
| Platform scope | `platform-boundary` |

**When a change violates a rule**, say so explicitly:

> **Rule drift:** `<rule>` — `<what violates it>` — suggest fix or ask to update the rule if intentional.

Do not expand scope to "fix" unrelated violations unless the user asks.

## 2. Tabled / deferred work

Canonical registry: [`docs/tabled.md`](../../docs/tabled.md).

- **During planning / design** — read `docs/tabled.md`; mention relevant rows
  ("tabled: X — include now or still defer?"). User usually reaches tabled.md before
  platform visions; remind if they forget at plan start.
- **When deferring** — append a row to `docs/tabled.md` (not only `notepad.md`).
- **When shipping** — remove the row from `docs/tabled.md`.
- **No nudge otherwise** — do not ping about tabled items outside planning/build context.

## 3. Naming and file structure

Follow [`naming.mdc`](naming.mdc) and [`agent-organization.mdc`](agent-organization.mdc).

Flag inconsistencies; run `company-brain doctor naming` and `company-brain migrate-names`
when bulk-renaming legacy wiki trees.

## 4. Documentation obligations

After **meaningful** work, update in order:

1. **`memory.md`** — prepend dated entry (newest on top)
2. **Department handbook** — `docs/agents/<dept>.md`
3. **`README.md`** — high-level map only
4. **`project_install.md`** — connect/onboard steps when platforms change
5. **`docs/tabled.md`** — defer or remove shipped backlog rows

**Plans:** `docs/plans/` is temporary; delete when build completes and steady-state docs
are updated. Do not create new doc files unless the user asks or a plan is needed.

Doc format: [`docs/doc-style.md`](../../docs/doc-style.md).

## 5. Human-readable docs and visuals

- **One mermaid diagram per major steady-state flow** — one summary paragraph under
  `## {Platform} — how it runs`, then the diagram; no duplicate ascii
  of the same flow.
- **Exclude onboarding agents from diagrams** — onboarding is one-time setup; graphs show
  how the system runs **after** setup (managers, persistent loops, dispatch).
- **Tables** for agent specs; short prose; link to code/config for detail.
- Deferred work: link to `docs/tabled.md` — no long "Not yet built" lists in handbooks.

## 6. Pre-ship checklist (always run)

```bash
ruff check .
ruff format --check .
pytest -q
company-brain doctor code
```

Doctor runs on every ship — no exceptions. Coherence / excess-file / repo cleaning
passes are **optional**; ask after large feature sections (see §7).

Use **no-sus-agent-doctor** skill for auth, billing, Gmail actuation, onboarding,
receipt routing, or security-sensitive changes.

## 7. Post-feature hygiene (ask, don't auto-run)

After a **large feature section** ships, ask the user:

> Would you like a **project coherence check** (doctor + naming + handbook vs code),
> **excess file scan**, or **repository cleaning** pass?

When they say yes, run the three-pass checklist in
[`docs/development.md`](../../docs/development.md) → **Post-feature hygiene checklist**:

1. **Cleanliness** — `ruff check .`, `ruff format --check .`, `pytest -q`, `git status --short`; no stray
   generated files tracked (gitignore local-only state), no leftover `docs/plans/*`.
2. **Coherence** — `company-brain doctor code` (+ `doctor llm` when keys exist), then
   docs-vs-code: handbook, README map, `project_install.md`, `config/*.yaml` keys have
   readers, `memory.md` entry, `docs/tabled.md` rows added/removed.
3. **Dead code** — `ruff check . --select F` for unused imports; manually grep new
   public symbols for callers (remove definitions with none), delete zero-logic
   placeholder modules (keep "concept only" as a `tabled.md` row), and consolidate
   duplicate helpers / orphaned config keys.
4. **Safety & deps** — secret scan the staged diff (`detect-secrets` / `gitleaks`;
   never commit `.env`/tokens), `pip-audit` when deps changed, new egress hosts in the
   `vmspec.toml` allow_list. Optional: `mypy`, `pytest --cov`, `codespell`, extended ruff.

Do not run destructive cleanup without explicit approval.
